{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569856","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569856"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:33:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:33:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22412"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22412","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22412"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.5,0.09,0.06,0.27,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15377"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109566"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15377","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15377"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22412"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91943"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"},{"type":"tags","id":"13199"},{"type":"tags","id":"13200"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"40911"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40913"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109566","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109566"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for a health check. He has a history of IgA nephropathy diagnosed five years ago. His only regular medication is ramipril. He does not identify as Aboriginal or Torres Strait Islander. He has no family history of cardiovascular disease. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His blood pressure is 128/82 mmHg. Recent investigations show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal cholesterol 5.8 mmol/L (2.0-5.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHDL 1.1 mmol/L (\u0026gt;1.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEstimated glomerular filtration rate 55 mL/min/1.73m2 (\u0026gt;90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine albumin:creatinine ratio 2.5 mg/mmol (\u0026lt;3.5).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following makes this patient inappropriate for cardiovascular risk assessment using the Australian CVD risk calculator?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Age less than 45 years","Blood pressure less than 130/85 mmHg","Total cholesterol greater than 5.5 mmol/L","Estimated glomerular filtration rate less than 60 mL/min/1.73m2","Urine albumin:creatinine ratio greater than 2.5 mg/mmol"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe Australian absolute cardiovascular disease risk calculator (CVDcheck) is designed for use in primary prevention of cardiovascular disease. However, there are specific criteria that determine when it is and is not appropriate to use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAge less than 45 years\u003C/strong\u003E makes this patient inappropriate for CVD risk assessment using the calculator. The tool is validated for use in people aged 45-79 years (or from 30 years in Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eestimated glomerular filtration rate less than 60 mL/min/1.73m\u003C/strong\u003E\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E and a \u003Cstrong\u003Eurine albumin:creatinine ratio greater than 2.5 mg/mmol\u003C/strong\u003E are not the appropriate kidney function indicators used for exclusion of CVDcheck use. Moderate to severe chronic kidney disease (defined as eGFR \u0026lt;45ml/min/1.73m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E, or persistent uACR \u0026gt;25mg/mmol in men, or \u0026gt;35mg/mmol in women) would make the patient automatically high-risk and inappropriate for the calculator. However, this patient\u0027s eGFR of 55 mL/min/1.73m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E is not low enough to meet this criterion and there is no significant albuminuria in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETotal cholesterol greater than 5.5 mmol/L \u003C/strong\u003Eand \u003Cstrong\u003Eblood pressure less than 130/85 mmHg\u003C/strong\u003E do not exclude use of the calculator. In fact, both cholesterol and blood pressure are variables used in the calculation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther factors that would make the calculator inappropriate for use include: presence of confirmed familial hypercholesterolaemia, previous cardiovascular events (myocardial infarction or cerebrovascular accident), or established atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The Australian CVD risk calculator is appropriate for people aged 45-79 years without known atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease.","Presence of moderate to severe chronic kidney disease, or familial hypercholesterolaemia necessitates alternative risk assessment approaches to the Australian CVD risk calculator.","First Nations peoples should be screened from age 30 years using the Australian CVD risk calculator."],"references":["Australian absolute cardiovascular disease risk calculator. In: National Vascular Disease Prevention Alliance [online]. Accessed 2025 Jun 25. Available at: https://www.cvdcheck.org.au/calculator"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91943"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22412"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91943","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91943"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-22T18:37:10